# This is approaching some beauty...
But it has nothing to do with the problem at hand, it's just an optimization using a parallel prefix algorithm, and using 2 threads to split up the work, due to not being able to access the environment to check amount of available threads.

The time used will drop with larger arrays. In this case, my submission ran at 0ms, while the general solution was about 3ms for the wastest and around 4ms on average.

The time complexity theoretically stays the same, but the work is split up, lowering the compute time.

If you want to try it out, the whole point here is to play with the amount of threads. Given we don't have enough information, it's guesswork. But e.g. 16 threads also seems to lower the time spent.


# Code
```
use std::sync::{Arc, Mutex};
use std::thread;
use std::boxed::Box;

impl Solution {
    fn xor_beauty(a: Vec<i32>) -> i32 {
        let a = Box::new(a);
        let a_ptr = Box::into_raw(a);
        let res = xor(unsafe { &*a_ptr });
        unsafe {
            drop(Box::from_raw(a_ptr));
        }
        res
    }
}

fn xor(arr: &'static Vec<i32>) -> i32 {
    let n = arr.len();
    let mut result = 0;
    if n == 0 {
        return result;
    }

    let mut num_threads = 2;
    if num_threads > n {
        num_threads = n;
    }
    let chunk_size = (n + num_threads - 1) / num_threads;
    let arr = Arc::new(arr);

    let mut handles = Vec::new();
    for i in 0..num_threads {
        let arr = arr.clone();
        let start = i * chunk_size;
        let end = std::cmp::min((i + 1) * chunk_size, n);
        handles.push(thread::spawn(move || {
            let mut xor = 0;
            for i in start..end {
                xor ^= arr[i];
            }
            xor
        }));
    }

    for handle in handles {
        result ^= handle.join().unwrap();
    }

    result
}

```

